Consider this code:

```
var a = [ [1,2,3], [4,5,6], [7,8,9] ];
_.map( a, _.max );
// gives [3, -Infinity, -Infinity]
```

I've written a detailed [answer on StackOverflow](http://stackoverflow.com/a/19656752/603003) why that issue occurs.

Basically, `_.max()` does only check whether the second argument is truthy or not. If it is truthy, it is treated as a callback function. That is the problem because `_.map()` passes the index as the second argument, so all iterations except the first one (because 0 != truthy) result in `-Infinity`.

Fix: check whether the callback argument is really a function.

```
if (!callback && isArray(collection)) {
// should be
if ( (!callback || typeof callback !== "function") && isArray(collection)) {
```

